 Lucien, Normand.","Breton: variant of <b>Saindo</b>, a habitational name from Le Saindo, a place in Morbihan, Brittany (France).","Alternatively, perhaps French: variant of   Sandon  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Sandon was born in 1380, in Belgrave, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Sandon, was 27 and his mother, Dionysia De La Roche, was 27. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Christiana. He died after 1400, in his hometown."},"et":{"1380–Aft 1400":"1380–pärast 1400","1380–1400":"1380–1400","1385–1400":"1385–1400","1400–1420":"1400–1420","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1354–Male":"1354–Surnud","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","Aft 1400":"pärast 1400","1400":"1400","1354":"1354","1420":"1420","1385":"1385","1380":"1380","after 1400":"pärast 1400","Belgrave, Leicester, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Leicester, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Belgrave, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Belgrave, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"," Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England"},"fi":{"1380–Aft 1400":"1380–1400 jälkeen","1380–1400":"1380–1400","1385–1400":"1385–1400","1400–1420":"1400–1420","1400–Female":"1400–Kuollut","1354–Male":"1354–Kuo